{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f3301abc-35c2-421a-8b61-4cf014e1327d","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Work/School (Azure AD) | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Multi-org Azure AD | `--auth MultiOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Example:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth Individual -o MyApi\n```\n\nYou can also add `--use-minimal-apis` for minimal API style, or `--use-controllers` for controller-based. Run `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"21303d2a-f66b-410c-8a8a-e6462cecafc2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":256,"requestId":"040E:3C6161:AAF1D6:D434B3:6A0128BF"},"id":"dfc578a7-2fef-4a3b-ba04-99d9415ad80e","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:54:32.250Z","parentId":"07f54797-0975-4f0d-85e0-9f790b1126b4"}
